\section{Triangle singularity}
\subsection{Essence}
\begin{frame}{What is the triangle singularity?}
Feynman approach
{\small 
$$
A(s_0,s_1,s_2) = 
g^3 \int \frac{d^4 k_1}{(2\pi)^4 i} \frac{1}{\Delta_1\Delta_2\Delta_3} =
\frac{g^3}{16\pi^2} \int_0^1\,\frac{\mathrm{d}x\,\mathrm{d}y\,\mathrm{d}z}{D}\delta(1-x-y-z),
$$}
{\small 
$$\Delta_i = m_i^2 - k_i^2, \quad D = x\,m_1^2 + y\,m_2^2 + z\,m_3^2 - x\,y\,s_0 - z\,x\,s_1 - y\,z\,s_2.$$}
%so we will consider $A(s_0,s_1,s_2)$, $s_0+i \varepsilon,s_1,s_2 \in \text{Re}$.\\ 
Positions of singularities are given by equations:
{\tiny \textcolor{purple}{[Landau, Nucl. Phys. {\bf 13}, 181 (1959)]} }
\begin{columns}
\begin{column}{0.3\paperwidth}
\centering
%\begin{figure}
   \begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=0.5cm and 0.75cm]
