\subsection*{Averaged polarimeter vector}

\begin{frame}[noframenumbering]{Averaged polarimeter vector}{}
  Defining the averaged polarimeter vector as $\overline{\alpha}_j = \int I_0\alpha_j \mathrm{d}^n \tau \; \big/\, \int I_0\,\mathrm{d}^n \tau$, we get:
  \begin{align*}
    \begin{array}{ccrl}
      \overline{\alpha_x}            & = & \left(-62.6 \pm 4.5_{-14.8}^{+8.4} \right) \times 10^{-3}\,,    &                                                                \\[1mm]
      \overline{\alpha_y}            & = & \left(+8.9 \pm 8.9_{-12.7}^{+9.1} \right) \times 10^{-3}\,,     & \text{  \color{red}(due to interference)}                      \\[1mm]
      \overline{\alpha_z}            & = & \left(-278.0 \pm 23.7_{-40.4}^{+12.6} \right) \times 10^{-3}\,, &                                                                \\[1mm]
      \overline{\left|\alpha\right|} & = & \left(669.4 \pm 9.3_{-10.4}^{+15.3} \right) \times 10^{-3}\,.   & \text{  \color{red}($\approx |\overline{\alpha}|\times 2.35$)}
    \end{array}
  \end{align*}
  First uncertainty is stat.\&syst (std.),
  second is model (extrema of alternative models).
