\begin{frame}{Local conclusion-III}
\begin{itemize}
\item The rescattering effects becomes very important when additioonal channels open and inelastisity rises.
\item The rescattering causes the wide smooth contributions to the waves and in some paricular case can produce resonance-like peaks.
\item $X \to K^\star K \to \pi Y_{(K\bar{K})}$ is ideal kinematics to produce narrow bump and sharp phase motion, which can be recognised in data.
\item $K^\star K \to f_0\pi$ rescattering makes the resonance-like signal $a_1(1420)$ at $1^{++}\,f_0\pi P-wave$. The fit is reasonable and comparable with the Briet-Wigner fit.
\item Analysis of $a_1\to K K \pi$ is needed.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}



\section{Conclusion}
\begin{frame}{Conclusion}
\begin{itemize}
%\item Huge data samples and advanced analysis tools make possible to see tiny features of strong interactions.
\item Rescattering in the triangle diagram is an important mechanism in hadron interactions.
\begin{itemize}
\item Simplest diagram to produce dynamic singularity which gives infinity.
\item Triangle singularity appears not only as anomalous threshold, but also as additional threshold above normal one in decay kinematics.
\item The position of singularity in the decay kinematics is given by simple condition of rescattering of real particles.
\end{itemize}
\item The full rescattering amplitude in presence of many inelastic channels makes the calculations more challenging. The experimental data on channels which rescatter to each others are needed.
\item We have now several hints that the triangle singularity plays important role in meson spectroscopy.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

