$$
g_{a_1 f_0 \pi}(\left. s \right|_{s=p_0^2}) = 
g^3 \int \frac{d^4 k_1}{(2\pi)^4 i} \frac{1}{\Delta_1\Delta_2\Delta_3} =
\frac{g^3}{16\pi^2} \int_0^1\mathrm{d}y\int_0^{1-y}\mathrm{d}z \, \frac{1}{D},
$$
{\tiny 
$$
\Delta_i = m_i^2-k_i^2 - i \epsilon,\quad
D =(1-y-z) m_1^2 + ym_2^2 + zm_3^2 - y(1-y-z)p_0^2 - z(1-z-y)p_1^2 - yz p_2^2.
$$
}
If Landau conditions {\tiny \textcolor{purple}{[Nucl. Phys. {\bf 13}, 181 (1959)]} } are satisfied, $g_{a_1 f_0 \pi} \sim \log(s-s_0)$. \\
{\tiny For a {\bf box loop}, $A\sim (s-s0)^{-1/2}$, for {\bf 5-leg loop } $A\sim (s-s_0)^{-1}$ (\textcolor{red}{pole})}.
}


