\section{Conclusion}
\frame{ \frametitle{Conclusion}
\begin{itemize}
\item Huge data samples and advanced analysis tools make possible to see tiny features of strong interactions.
\item $a_1(1420)$ is definitely interesting object to study.
\item $a_1(1420)$ can be explained by triangle singularity, {\it resonance-like} effect of appearance of logarithmic branch point (\textcolor{red}{not a pole}) in amplitude caused by rescattering of kaons.
\begin{itemize}
\item Sharp phase motion $\sim 90^\circ$ is obtained with respect to $a_1\to \rho\pi$. 
\item The magnitude of $\sigma(a_1\to f_0\pi)$ is of the order of experimental value. Better knowledge of coupling is required. 
\item Future precise studies of $a_1(1260)$ should shine light to that subject.
%From other hand the calculated amplitude could be used to fit the signal. 
\end{itemize}
%\item {\small Not every bump is a resonance..} $\to$ {\bf Not every bump, even with phase motion is new resonance}.
\end{itemize}
