\begin{frame}{Typical problems in HEP analysis}
Workflow:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Course selection on event topology (done centrally, sometimes online) %: python/DSL to configure C++ algorithms 
  \item Pre-Selection (done via distributed computation grid) %: python/DSL to configure C++ algorithms
  \item Fine event selection -- NN/BDT %: python/C++
  \item Extraction of physics %: python/C++
\end{enumerate}
\begin{alertblock}{}
  Julia fits everywhere (in principle). Currently on 3 and 4 since done in small groups.  
\end{alertblock}
\begin{exampleblock}{Common tools}
  The main framework is ROOT (C++, python binding).
  \begin{itemize}
    \item TMVA: BDT, NN training
    \item RooFit: flexible model building
    \item Minuit: robust minimization package with objective stopping criterion 
  \end{itemize}
\end{exampleblock}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Modeling particle spectra}
  \begin{columns}
    \begin{column}{0.50\textwidth}
      Construction complex parametric PDFs:
      \begin{itemize}
        \item Non-standard densities (complex interferences $|A+B|^2$)
        \item Non-linear dependence on parameters
        \item Combinations of distributions (mixed models: signal/background)
        \item Parameter constraints
        \item Unbinned (extended) maximum likelihood fitting 
      \end{itemize}
    \end{column}
    \begin{column}{0.45\textwidth}
      \includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{XicK_fit_unconstrained.pdf}      
    \end{column}
  \end{columns}
\centering
\begin{alertblock}{}\centering
  Parameters with value and property is a part of the model.
\end{alertblock}
\vspace{5mm}
[show an example with AlgebraPDF.jl]
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Summary}
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Julia is well suited for HEP problems:
      mathematical computation on large data samples, statistical modeling.
    \item Julia in analysis of $\Omega_c^{**}$ states Julia in LHCb
    \begin{center}
      https://github.com/mmikhasenko/OmegacXXinOmegab2XicKpi/
    \end{center}    
    \begin{itemize}
      \item Analysis of mass spectrum (\texttt{AlgebraPDF.jl})
      \item Angular analysis, hypothesis testing  ({\small\texttt{ThreeBodyDecay.jl}, \texttt{PartialWaveFunctions.jl}})
      \item Plotting for publication ({\small\texttt{Plots.jl: gr(), pgfplotsx()}})
      \item Re-running the full analysis chain for systematics studies ({\small\texttt{julia> run(`dvc repro`)}})
    \end{itemize}
  \end{itemize}
  \centering
  \begin{center}
    Looking forward to seeing more Julia in HEP
