\begin{frame}{More on the $\Tcc$ width}
  \begin{block}{}
    \centering
    The natural \textbf{width} is the key observable of \textbf{compositeness}
  \end{block}
  \begin{itemize}
    \item The peak position is well fixed, $\sim -400\,$keV below $D^{*+}D^0$
    \item effective range (or $g$) is the only shape parameter
    % \item $g \to \in$ $\Rightarrow$ 
    \item $g \to 0$ $\Rightarrow$ small compositeness (the natural width is zero)
    \item $g \to \infty$ $\Rightarrow$ large compositeness ($\Gamma_\Tcc$ goes to the \textbf{\color{cola}saturation limit})
    \item How different $\Gamma_{\Tcc}$ from the \textbf{\color{cola}saturation limit} determines the compositeness
  \end{itemize}\pause
  \begin{itemize}
    \item But what is {\color{cola}this limit value}?
    \begin{itemize}
      \item $48\,$keV: not-iterated OPE (LHCb model)~\paper{LHCb, NC 13 (2022) 3351}
      \item $30\,$keV: no OPE at all~\paper{MM, \textsc{Tcc2DDpi.jl @ GitHub}}
      \item $75\,$keV: in two-body approximation~\paper{Albaladejo, M. (2021)}
      \item $56\,$keV: with all three-body effects~\paper{Meng-Lin Du et al. (2021)}
    \end{itemize}\pause
    \item {\color{colc}Experimentally}: the fit pushes the width to higher values.
    \begin{itemize}
      \item Low limit in the default model, $\Gamma_{\Tcc} > 20\,$keV at $95\%\,$CL.
      \item BW model: the fit with the free-parameter width gives $410 \pm 165\,$keV.
    \end{itemize}
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

